msContents.summary: This manuscript is a Sequentiary (Prosar) for Dominican Use from the late fifteenth or early sixteenth century, probably copied in the royal convent of Saint-Louis in Poissy, France. It contains texts and musical notation for sequences, chants sung at the Mass between the Alleluia and the reading of the Gospels. The chants are arranged to follow the Temporal (fols. 1r-30r) and Sanctoral (fols. 30r-133v) cycles, with additional chants and prayers at the end of the volume, with feminine forms used in two of the prayers (fols. 172r, 175r). The latest canonization reflected in the Sanctoral cycle is Catherine of Siena, canonized in 1461 (fols. 57r-59v); Antoninus of Florence, canonized in 1524, is not included. The Sanctoral cycle also includes sequences for the Dominican saints Dominic, Peter Martyr, and Thomas Aquinas, and two sequences for Saint Louis, founder of Poissy. A few interlinear translations and marginal notations in French have been added by later hands (fols. 87r-91r, 94r, 95v).

supportDesc.extent: 181+i; 173 x 114 mm bound to 180 x 125 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, 1-181, upper right recto

p.signatures: Some signatures visible with letter designating the quire and tally marks for the leaf

p.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords in ink, lower right last verso, visible or partially visible in quires 1-4, 7, 9, 12, (fol. 8v, 16v, 24v, 32v, 56v, 72v, 96v)

layoutDesc.layout: One column of five lines of text and five four-line red staves with square musical notation (fols. 1r-171r) or one column of seventeen to nineteen lines (fols. 171v-181r), frame-ruled in lead with widely spaced horizontal rules for the text; prickings top and bottom margins, a few folios with prickings in the outer margins; written area : 105 x 60 mm (fols. 1r-171r), 105 x 65 mm (fols. 171v-181r)

decoDesc.decoNote: Opening initial of each chant height of text line plus staff, generally alternating between red and blue, except for the first, a puzzle initial in red and blue (fol. 1r); one-line alternating red and blue initials within chant texts; two- and one-line alternating red and blue initials and majuscules touched in pale yellow in prayers (fols. 171v-181r); guide letters within initials; rubrication in red

binding.p: Modern (?) orange rough suede binding over wooden boards cut flush with the book block (possibly original boards); spine with five slightly raised bands, edges gilt and possibly gauffered

history.provenance: Royal abbey of St.-Louis at Poissy; ownership inscription, possibly seventeenth-century, of a sous-prieure (sub-prioress, inside front cover)
